While both can represent a 2D point, `cc.p()` is the standard factory function that creates a proper `cc.Point`:

**cc.p(x, y)**
- Creates a `cc.Point` object recognized by all Cocos2d-x APIs
- Compatible with `cc.pAdd`, `cc.pSub`, `cc.pDistance`, etc.
- Works with `setPosition(point)`, `drawDot(point, ...)`, etc.

**Plain object {x: 100, y: 200}**
- May work in some APIs that only check for `.x` and `.y` properties
- NOT guaranteed to work with all cc.p* math utilities
- May fail in JSB/native builds where C++ expects specific types

```typescript
// Recommended
const pos = cc.p(100, 200);
node.setPosition(pos);
const dist = cc.pDistance(pos, cc.p(0, 0)); // works

// Risky
const obj = {x: 100, y: 200};
node.setPosition(obj);  // may work in HTML5 but not JSB
// cc.pDistance(obj, cc.p(0, 0)); // may fail
```

Always use `cc.p()` for consistency and cross-platform safety.

```typescript
class GridConverter {
    private _cellSize: cc.Size;
    private _origin: cc.Point;

    constructor(cellSize: cc.Size, origin: cc.Point = cc.p(0, 0)) {
        this._cellSize = cellSize;
        this._origin = origin;
    }

    gridToWorld(col: number, row: number): cc.Point {
        return cc.p(
            this._origin.x + col * this._cellSize.width + this._cellSize.width / 2,
            this._origin.y + row * this._cellSize.height + this._cellSize.height / 2
        );
    }

    worldToGrid(worldPos: cc.Point): {col: number; row: number} {
        const local = cc.pSub(worldPos, this._origin);
        return {
            col: Math.floor(local.x / this._cellSize.width),
            row: Math.floor(local.y / this._cellSize.height)
        };
    }

    getCellRect(col: number, row: number): cc.Rect {
        return cc.rect(
            this._origin.x + col * this._cellSize.width,
            this._origin.y + row * this._cellSize.height,
            this._cellSize.width,
            this._cellSize.height
        );
    }
}

// Usage:
const grid = new GridConverter(cc.size(32, 32), cc.p(16, 16));
const worldPos = grid.gridToWorld(3, 5);  // center of cell (3,5)
const cell = grid.worldToGrid(cc.p(120, 180));  // which cell?
const rect = grid.getCellRect(3, 5);  // bounding rect of cell
```
